#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:4
msgid "Fixture functions using \"yield\" / context manager integration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:10
msgid ""
"pytest-2.4 allows fixture functions to seamlessly use a ``yield`` instead of "
"a ``return`` statement to provide a fixture value while otherwise fully "
"supporting all other fixture features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:14
msgid "Let's look at a simple standalone-example using the ``yield`` syntax::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:16
msgid ""
"# content of test_yield.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.yield_fixture\n"
"def passwd():\n"
"    print (\"\\nsetup before yield\")\n"
"    f = open(\"/etc/passwd\")\n"
"    yield f.readlines()\n"
"    print (\"teardown after yield\")\n"
"    f.close()\n"
"\n"
"def test_has_lines(passwd):\n"
"    print (\"test called\")\n"
"    assert passwd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:32
msgid ""
"In contrast to :ref:`finalization through registering callbacks "
"<finalization>`, our fixture function used a ``yield`` statement to provide "
"the lines of the ``/etc/passwd`` file. The code after the ``yield`` "
"statement serves as the teardown code, avoiding the indirection of "
"registering a teardown callback function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:38
msgid "Let's run it with output capturing disabled::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:40
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q -s test_yield.py\n"
"\n"
"setup before yield\n"
"test called\n"
".teardown after yield\n"
"\n"
"1 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:48
msgid ""
"We can also seamlessly use the new syntax with ``with`` statements. Let's "
"simplify the above ``passwd`` fixture::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:51
msgid ""
"# content of test_yield2.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.yield_fixture\n"
"def passwd():\n"
"    with open(\"/etc/passwd\") as f:\n"
"        yield f.readlines()\n"
"\n"
"def test_has_lines(passwd):\n"
"    assert len(passwd) >= 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:63
msgid ""
"The file ``f`` will be closed after the test finished execution because the "
"Python ``file`` object supports finalization when the ``with`` statement "
"ends."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:67
msgid ""
"Note that the yield fixture form supports all other fixture features such as "
"``scope``, ``params``, etc., thus changing existing fixture functions to use "
"``yield`` is straightforward."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:73
msgid ""
"While the ``yield`` syntax is similar to what :py:func:`contextlib."
"contextmanager` decorated functions provide, with pytest fixture functions "
"the part after the \"yield\" will always be invoked, independently from the "
"exception status of the test function which uses the fixture. This behaviour "
"makes sense if you consider that many different test functions might use a "
"module or session scoped fixture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:83
msgid "Discussion and future considerations / feedback"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:85
msgid "There are some topics that are worth mentioning:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:87
msgid ""
"usually ``yield`` is used for producing multiple values. But fixture "
"functions can only yield exactly one value. Yielding a second fixture value "
"will get you an error. It's possible we can evolve pytest to allow for "
"producing multiple values as an alternative to current parametrization. For "
"now, you can just use the normal :ref:`fixture parametrization <fixture-"
"parametrize>` mechanisms together with ``yield``-style fixtures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:96
msgid ""
"lastly ``yield`` introduces more than one way to write fixture functions, so "
"what's the obvious way to a newcomer?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/yieldfixture.rst:99
msgid ""
"If you want to feedback or participate in discussion of the above topics, "
"please join our :ref:`contact channels`, you are most welcome."
msgstr ""
